For passengers, the elevation change can trigger altitude sensitivity even before reaching Breckenridge proper at 9,600 feet. I've seen people feel lightheaded or nauseous during the drive, particularly if they're coming from sea level locations. Most shuttle drivers carry water and know to suggest slower movements when loading and unloading, but not all passengers realize this is elevation-related rather than motion sickness.

